abstract: “Better Call Saul” is a great show. It will improve when, at long last, Saul gets the call.
snippet: “Better Call Saul” is a great show. It will improve when, at long last, Saul gets the call.
lead_paragraph: There was a death in the Season 2 finale of “Better Call Saul,” an unceremonious shot to the head that felled a hapless truck driver employed by the cartel. But I’d argue that the real brutality came from the white-collar side of this two-pronged tale. The up-close depiction of brothers locked in a bitter psychological war can be far harder to watch than murder.

lead_paragraph: In a wood-paneled conference room at Stanford University, a score of scholars, many of them eminent and some from as far away as Johannesburg and Beijing, gathered last month to compare philosophical notions of hierarchy and equality.

lead_paragraph: When Porsche added the Cayenne sport utility vehicle to its lineup in 2003, loyalists reacted as if Beelzebub himself would ride in to usher in doomsday. Funny how it became the best-selling vehicle the company makes.

abstract: Donnie Walsh, a former Knicks president, advised that Phil Jackson, the current president, should know how his roster will look before deciding on a coach.
snippet: Donnie Walsh, a former Knicks president, advised that Phil Jackson, the current president, should know how his roster will look before deciding on a coach.
lead_paragraph: With another playoff-less season concluding in Indiana on Tuesday night, Phil Jackson has the always contentious chore of anointing yet another Knicks head coach. But before he dwells on who’s got next, he may well want to heed an experienced voice of the not-too-distant past.

lead_paragraph: Will Smith, a former defensive end for the New Orleans Saints who played on their Super Bowl championship team in 2009-10, was shot and killed in New Orleans late Saturday, the authorities said.

abstract: “Catastrophe” starts Season 2 by finding Sharon and Rob coping with a second child. And Meryl Streep rocks out in “Ricki and the Flash.”
snippet: “Catastrophe” starts Season 2 by finding Sharon and Rob coping with a second child. And Meryl Streep rocks out in “Ricki and the Flash.”
lead_paragraph: “Catastrophe” zooms ahead in Season 2 to find Sharon and Rob, those accidental parents, steering into the skid of life. Meryl Streep rocks out in a Bo Derek hairstyle in “Ricki and the Flash.” And Al Jazeera America presents its last documentary before going off the air on Tuesday.

abstract: Going door to door, a Los Angeles-based activist group tries to reduce prejudice against transgender people. A new study finds that it works.
snippet: Going door to door, a Los Angeles-based activist group tries to reduce prejudice against transgender people. A new study finds that it works.
lead_paragraph: Dave Fleischer — a short, bald, gay, Jewish 61-year-old with bulging biceps and a distaste for prejudice — knocked on the front door of a modest home in a middle-class neighborhood on the west side of Los Angeles. It was an enthusiastic knuckle-thump, the kind that arouses suspicion from dogs in yards halfway down the block but, crucially, can also be heard by humans watching cable news at high volume.

abstract: Season 2 of this Amazon Prime show picks up with its stars expecting a baby a couple of years after an unplanned pregnancy led, eventually, to romance.
snippet: Season 2 of this Amazon Prime show picks up with its stars expecting a baby a couple of years after an unplanned pregnancy led, eventually, to romance.
lead_paragraph: Love is a mess. It’s awkward and clumsy and can lead to the uncomfortable gestation of a small human.

abstract: The Yippie-era magazine devoted to marijuana culture seeks to go mainstream, with branded socks, furniture and, eventually, bars and casinos.
snippet: The Yippie-era magazine devoted to marijuana culture seeks to go mainstream, with branded socks, furniture and, eventually, bars and casinos.
lead_paragraph: Picture a mood-lit Las Vegas casino, at first glance indistinguishable from any other pleasure palace on the Strip: salarymen hunch over $20 blackjack tables as waitresses with plunging necklines circle the floor.
